Place the small compass near the north pole of the magnet and make a dot
 at each end of the needle using a pencil not encased in metal.
\layout Enumerate

Move the compass forward until its south pole points at the previous north
 pole dot, and make a new dot at the north pole.
\layout Enumerate

Repeat 3 until the series of dots reaches the south pole of the magnet or
 the edge of the paper.
\layout Enumerate

In a similar manner, trace enough lines to map the magnetic field over the
 entire paper.
 Take points about 0.5 cm apart near the poles and about 2 cm apart near
 the middle of the magnet.
\layout Enumerate

There are two points, called neutral points, near each end of the magnet
 where the magnet's field and the earth's field are equal and opposite and
 so cancel.
 At these points, the compass will align in no particular direction.
 Try to locate these points by tracing very carefully the lines of force
 in the neighborhood of the poles.
